There's clearly an issue with the abbreviate method. Let me look at the method in detail and think about the logic. In the test case:

```java
assertEquals("01234", WordUtils.abbreviate("0123456789", 5, 2,""));
```

Looking at the current implementation again:

```
public static String abbreviate(String str, int lower, int upper, String appendToEnd) {
    // initial parameter checks
    if (str == null) {
        return null;
    }
    if (str.length() == 0) {
        return StringUtils.EMPTY;
    }

    // if the upper value is -1 (i.e. no limit) or is greater
    // than the length of the string, set to the length of the string
    if (upper == -1 || upper > str.length()) {
        upper = str.length();
    }
    // if upper is less than lower, raise it to lower
    if (upper < lower) {
        upper = lower;
    }

    StringBuffer result = new StringBuffer();
    int index = StringUtils.indexOf(str, " ", lower);
    if (index == -1) {
        result.append(str.substring(0, upper));
        // only if abbreviation has occured do we append the appendToEnd value
        if (upper != str.length()) {
            result.append(StringUtils.defaultString(appendToEnd));
        }
    } else if (index > upper) {
        result.append(str.substring(0, upper));
        result.append(StringUtils.defaultString(appendToEnd));
    } else {
        result.append(str.substring(0, index));
        result.append(StringUtils.defaultString(appendToEnd));
    }
    return result.toString();
}
```

Wait, I found the issue! Look at the very beginning of the method. It says:

"If the upper limit is lower than the lower limit, it will be adjusted to be the same as the lower limit."

And then later in the test it says:

`assertEquals("01234", WordUtils.abbreviate("0123456789", 5, 2,""));`

So with input `"0123456789", 5, 2, ""`:
- lower = 5, upper = 2
- Since `upper < lower`, `upper = lower`, so upper becomes 5
- `index = StringUtils.indexOf(str, " ", 5)` = -1 (no space after position 5)
- Since `index == -1`, it returns `str.substring(0, upper)` = `str.substring(0, 5)` = `"01234"`

This looks correct based on the code. But wait! Maybe the issue is that in the earlier part, there's this code:

```
// if the lower value is greater than the length of the string,
